com.wm.xmldata

Interface XmlDataTreeCursor

  • All Superinterfaces:
    XmlDataCursor
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    XmlDataTreeCursorImpl

    public interface XmlDataTreeCursor
extends XmlDataCursor

    See glossary of terms

    Overview

    The XmlDataTreeCursor provides additional capabilities beyond those of the XmlDataCursor. In particular, repeating values can be navigated as if they were flattened scalar values rather than arrays so that additional methods such as nextItem() and previousItem() position to next or previous individual item in the array. This is achieved by internally maintaining a current-index in this cursor that specifies an offset within repeating-values.

    There are also additional methods such as firstItem() and lastItem() that that position on the very first and very last items in the XmlData object by setting the current-index as appropriate. There are also the deleteForward() and deleteBackward() methods that are index-aware and update the current-index after deleting an individual item. Indexed XmlDataCursor accessors such as getValue(), getItem, getContent(), setItem(), setValue(), and setContent() behave slightly differently for XmlDataTreeCursor. When the index is omitted, the item at the current-index is referenced (contrasted to an XmlDataCursor for which an omitted index implies that there is only one item).

    Finally, the XmlDataTreeCursor "object" methods have the same basic behavior as the XmlDataCursor "object" methods except that any method call that changes the current-position also resets the current-index to zero. The XmlDataCursor concepts such as current-position, current-object, and current-tag are exactly the same for XmlDataTreeCursor. When cursors are stacked during tree traversal, these concepts apply to the cursor most recently pushed onto the cursor stack. Other concepts such as current-tree-position are unique to XmlDataTreeCursor.

    XmlDataTreeCursor also supports navigation through a hierarchy of XmlData objects using the parent(), firstChild(), and lastChild() methods. These methods maintain a stack of cursors. Invoking lastChild() or firstChild() pushes the current cursor onto a stack and creates a new cursor for the child content. The parent() method pops the top of the cursor stack and restores the parent as the current XmlData object. It is also possible to navigate through nested XmlData structures in document order using the methods nextInOrder() and previousInOrder().

    Glossary of terms:

    • current-cursor - the cursor navigating the current level of the tree. Methods such as firstChild() push the current-cursor onto a stack and allocate a new cursor in order to navigate the child content of the current-value. The newly created cursor becomes the current-cursor. Methods such as parent() pop the top cursor from the internal cursor stack and the popped cursor then becomes the current-cursor.
    • child -- a child is a member of the current-value. Only group-values or a complex-values can have children. Group-values with no members or complex-values with no group-value content are defined to have no children
    • current-index an index into the current-object of repeating values. The current-index is maintained by this cursor. If repeating values are not present, the current-index is zero. When initially positioned on an object, the current-index is set to zero (the first or only item). Subsequent calls to nextItem() and similar methods cause the index to be incremented. Subsequents calls to previousItem() and similar methods cause the index to be decremented. When the current-index is positioned on the last item in the current-object, a subsequent call to nextItem() resets the current index to zero and points to the first item in the next tag-object-pair. When the current-index is positioned on the first item in the current-object, a subsequent call to previousItem() sets the current-index to point at the last item in the previous tag-object-pair. The combination of current-object and current-index uniquely identify the current-item
    • current-item - the item stored at the current-tree-position. If the current-tag is an element-tag or a group-tag, the current-item is the same as the current-value and will be either a simple-value, group-value, or complex-value. If the current-tag is an indirect-tag, then the current-item is an indirect-item.
    • current-value - the value stored at the current-tree-position. If the current-tag is an element-tags or a group-tag, the current-value is the same as the current-item and will be either a simple-value, group-value, or complex-value. If the current-tag is an any-tag or substitution-tag, the current-value is the value stored indirectly in the indirect-item that is the current-item.
    • current-tree-position - the combination of the current-object and the current-index from the current-cursor.
    • in-order -- the same as DOM document order. The natural order in which XML element nodes are traversed in a document. Is is essentially the order in which element tags are encountered during a sequential scan of an XML document. The nextInOrder() and previousInOrder() methods navigate through an XMlData infoset using in-order traversal.

      • currentIndex

        int currentIndex()
        Returns the index of the current-item for an object that contains repeating values. For a non-repeating value, the index is always zero ( because there is only 1 item).
        Returns:
        int value of the current-index. An unpositioned cursor returns -1.

      • deleteBackward

        boolean deleteBackward()
        Deletes the current-item and positions the cursor on the previous item. If the first item of the current-object is deleted, the cursor is positioned on the last or only item of the previous object. If there is no previous object, the cursor is unpositioned. Returns false if there are no more previous items and leaves the cursor unpositioned.
        Returns:
        true if more items remain in the backward direction

      • deleteForward

        boolean deleteForward()
        Deletes the current-item and positions the cursor on the next item. If the last item of the C is deleted, the cursor is positioned on the first or only item of the next object. If there is no next object, the cursor is unpositioned.
        Returns:
        true if more items remain in the forward direction.

      • depth

        int depth()
        Return the stacked cursor depth. Initially zero. For every invocation of firstChild() or lastChild() that returns true, the depth increases by one. For every invocation of parent() that returns true, the depth decreases by one.
        Returns:
        the number of stacked cursors (not counting the current cursor).

      • firstChild

        boolean firstChild()
        Positions this cursor on the first child of the current-value. Only group-values and complex-values with group-value content have children. If the current-value does not contain a child, (for example it contains a String or an empty IData), false is returned and the cursor position remains unchanged. If the current-value has one or more children, the current-cursor is pushed onto a stack and a new cursor is positioned on the first child item. If it is necessary to obtain a cursor on empty content, consider method XmlDataCursor.getValueCursor(int...).
        Returns:
        true if the current-value has children
        Throws:
        XmlDataException.UnpositionedCursor - when the cursor is not positioned

      • firstItem

        boolean firstItem()
        Positions this cursor on the first item. The first tag-object-pair becomes the current-object. If the first object is an array (repeating values), the cursor is positioned on first item in the array by setting the current-index to zero. In other words, the first item is the first member of a repeating values Object array. If the first object is not an array, then the first item is simply the first object.
        Returns:
        true if there is a first item.

      • insertItemAfter

        void insertItemAfter(java.lang.Object item)
        Inserts an item after the current-item in a repeating value. An item may be either a value or an indirect item. The item must be compatible with the current tag. For element and groups, this method behaves exactly like insertValueAfter(XmlDataContentTag, Object) and the item is treated like a value. If the current tag is a substitution tag, a properly formatted substitution-item must be provided. If the current tag is an any tag, a properly formatted any-item must be provided. This is unlike insertValueBefore(XmlDataContentTag, Object) because the indirect is not provided but created. This method differs from XmlDataCursor.insertItemBefore(Object, int) because and index is not required. When no index is specified the current index is used.
        Parameters:
        item - the item to insert
        Throws:
        XmlDataException.UnpositionedCursor - when the cursor is not positioned

      • insertItemBefore

        void insertItemBefore(java.lang.Object item)
        Inserts an item before the current-item in a repeating item object. An item may be either a value or an indirect item. The item must be compatible with the current tag. For element and groups, this method behaves exactly like insertValueAfter(XmlDataContentTag, Object) and the item is treated like a value. If the current tag is a substitution tag, a properly formatted substitution-item must be provided. If the current tag is an any tag, a properly formatted any-item must be provided. This is unlike insertValueBefore(XmlDataContentTag, Object) because the indirect is not provided but created. This method differs from XmlDataCursor.insertItemBefore(Object, int) because and index is not required. When no index is specified the current index is used.
        Parameters:
        item - the item to insert
        Throws:
        XmlDataException.UnpositionedCursor - when the cursor is not positioned

      • insertValueAfter

        void insertValueAfter(XmlDataContentTag tag,
                      java.lang.Object value)
        Insert a value and value-tag after the current-item. For element-tags and group-tags, this method inserts the value directly into the repeating value array and the tag is not used and may be null. If a tag is specified, it must match the current-tag. For substitution-tags and any-tags, an indirect item is created from the value-tag and value and is inserted into the repeating values after the current-index. This method is an extension beyond XmlDataCursor.insertValueAfter(XmlDataContentTag, Object, int) because this method allows insertion without specifying an index (the current index is used). XmlDataCursor does not support insertAfter without an index.
        Parameters:
        tag - the tag used to construct the indirect item
        value - the value used to construct the indirect item
        Throws:
        XmlDataException.UnpositionedCursor - when the cursor is not positioned

This method is an extension beyond XmlDataCursor.insertValueBefore(XmlDataContentTag, Object, int) because this method allows insert without specifying an index (the current index is used).       • lastChild

        boolean lastChild()
        This cursor is positioned on the last child value of the current-value. Only group-values and complex-values with group-value content have children. If the current-value does not contain a child, (fox example it contains a String or an empty IData), false is returned and cursor position remains unchanged. If the current-value has one or more children, the current-cursor is pushed onto a stack and a new cursor is positioned on the last child item. If it is necessary to obtain a cursor on empty content, consider method XmlDataCursor.getValueCursor(int...).
        Returns:
        true if the current-value has children
        Throws:
        XmlDataException.UnpositionedCursor - when the cursor is not positioned

      • lastItem

        boolean lastItem()
        Positions this cursor on the last item. The last tag-object-pair becomes the current-object. If the last object is an array (repeating values), the cursor is positioned on the last item in the array by setting the current-index to the length of the array minus one.
        Returns:
        true if positioned to the last item.

      • nextInOrder

        java.lang.Integer nextInOrder()
        Positions to the next in-order item. If there is no next item (at the current tree level), the cursor is positioned on the first item in the parent's next item. If the cursor is unpositioned, the cursor is positioned on the first item in the XmlData infoset tree.
        Returns:
        the change in tree depth (or null if there is no next in order)

      • nextItem

        boolean nextItem()
        Positions on the next item. When more than one item is associated with a tag (repeating values in an array), the cursor is positioned on the next item in the array (as if the array had been flattened) by incrementing the current-index. If already positioned on the last item of the current-object, the cursor is positioned on the first item of the next object. If there is no next item, the cursor remains unchanged.
        Returns:
        true if there is a next item.

      • nextItem

        boolean nextItem(XmlDataContentTag tag)
        Positions this cursor on the next item with the specified tag. The match is based on the current-tag. For example, if a substitution-item is present, the match comparison is performed against the substitution-tag. When repeating values are present and the search tag matches the current-tag, only the current-index is advanced and the current-position remains unchanged (unless already positioned on the last item of a repeating value). In order to find the next item based on the item's value-tag, which is probably more typical, use the nextValueTag(XmlDataContentTag) method. The tag match is based on the partial-name (it does not include the particle-id).
        Parameters:
        tag - the tag that is compared to item tags
        Returns:
        true if the item is found

      • nextValueTag

        boolean nextValueTag(XmlDataContentTag tag)
        Positions this cursor on the next item with a value-tag that matches the search tag. For normal elements, this is the same as nextItem(XmlDataContentTag). However, for any-items and substitution-items, the nextItem()'s value-tag is used for comparison. This method is more easily used for a general search than the nextItem(XmlDataContentTag) method because the user can search without concern for whether the items are normal elements or indirect-items. The tag match is based on the partial-name (it does not include the particle-id).
        Parameters:
        tag - the tag which is compared t0 item value-tags
        Returns:
        true if the the next matching item is found

      • parent

        boolean parent()
        Moves the XmlDataTreeCursor up one level by popping the top-level cursor from the internal stack of cursor.. Returns false if already at the top level. Destroys the current cursor before moving up one level. If firstChild() or lastChild() had never been invoked on this cursor, the parent() method will always return false.
        Returns:
        True if the current-item has a parent. If already at top, no action is performed and false is returned.

      • previousInOrder

        java.lang.Integer previousInOrder()
        Positions to the previous in-order item. If there is no previous item, the cursor is positioned on the last child in the parent's previous item. If the cursor is unpositioned, the cursor is positioned on the last item in the XmlData infoset tree.
        Returns:
        the change in tree depth (or null if there is no previous item)

      • previousItem

        boolean previousItem()
        Positions this cursor on the previous item. When more that one item is associated with a tag (repeating values in an array). the cursor is positioned on the previous item in the array. If already positioned on the first item, the cursor is positioned on the previous item (or last item in the previous object if it is also an array). If there is no previous items, the cursor remains unchanged.
        Returns:
        true if there i a previous value
